        {
          "type": "reasoning",
          "text": "The user is asking if having a shared `gen_cloud.exe` created from C++ is acceptable per the course policies in AGENTS.md.\n\nLet me reference the relevant policies:\n\nFrom § 4.9:\n- \"3. Эталоны генерятся на лету, в репо не хранятся.\"\n- \"Эталон считает независимая референс-реализация\"\n\nFrom § 6.1 about task 3:\n- \"Mass test (tasks 3-4): облака генератор gen_cloud --size --seed (std::mt19937, fixed seed), sizes 10 / 100 / 10⁶; data in build/ under .gitignore.\"\n\nThe policy says gen_cloud should be an independent generator. The C++ gen_cloud writes text to stdout. The C program reads text from stdin. They communicate through text (pipes). This is completely language-agnostic.\n\nAlso, § 4.4 says tasks should be implemented twice (C and C++), but gen_cloud is not a task from § 6 — it's testing infrastructure. § 4.8 says \"Голая версия — с первой задачи; промышленная — когда задача доросла\" — gen_cloud is a testing tool, not a task. It makes sense to have one version that both C and C++ programs use.\n\nAnd from § 4.9 point 1: \"Одна точка входа в проект\" — one entry point. Having one gen_cloud for both languages is actually more aligned with this.\n\nSo my assessment is: yes, it's fine per the course policies. The gen_cloud is testing infrastructure, not a \"task\" that must be done in both languages.",
