        {
          "type": "reasoning",
          "text": "The user is asking whether they should also `free(points)` at the end of the program, since they already `free(s)`.\n\nThis is a design/memory management question. Let me think about it in the context of their learning program.\n\nIn a typical long-running application, yes - you should free all allocated memory. But in a short-lived CLI program that's about to exit, the OS will reclaim all memory anyway. This is an accepted practice in C.\n\nThe course policies (§ 4.1) say to check for garbage in diffs but don't specifically mandate freeing all memory before exit. However, with `free(s)` already done, `free(points)` would be consistent.\n\nBut there's a practical consideration: ASan (`/fsanitize=address`) detects memory leaks by default. When the program exits, ASan reports leaked memory. The user might see leak warnings from ASan.\n\nLet me give a balanced answer.",
