        {
          "type": "reasoning",
          "text": "The user is running into an issue with `findstr` in their batch file. The error message shows:\n\n```\nFINDSTR: /C Їа®ЇгбЄ Ґвбп\nFINDSTR: /  Їа®ЇгбЄ Ґвбп\nFINDSTR: /1 Їа®ЇгбЄ Ґвбп\nFINDSTR: /. Їа®ЇгбЄ Ґвбп\n```\n\nThe Russian text \"Їа®ЇгбЄ Ґвбп\" looks like CP1251 text displayed in the wrong encoding. It's probably \"пропускается\" (skipped) or something similar.\n\nBut the key issue is that `findstr` is complaining about the `/C` option syntax. Looking at the user's command:\n\n```\nfindstr /C\" 1.\" build\\err.txt > nul\n```\n\nThis is incorrect syntax. `findstr` requires a colon between `/C` and the search string: `/C:\" 1.\"` not `/C\" 1.\"`.\n\nAlso, there could be a Russian text encoding issue with `findstr` on Windows — the earlier journal entry (2026-06-30/07-01) mentioned:\n\n> если в .bat сделать findstr /C:\"Строка 1.\" build\\err.txt > nul то слово \"Строка\" не будет нормально интерпретировано, т.к. findstr берёт аргументы не в chcp 1251, а в другой кодировке\n\nSo `findstr` with Russian text in CP1251 doesn't work properly. The user worked around this by searching for `\" 1.\"` instead of the full Russian text — searching for the line number with surrounding spaces/dots.\n\nBut in the current code, the command syntax is wrong: `findstr /C\" 1.\"` should be `findstr /C:\" 1.\"`. And also `findstr /C:\"2 3 bam\"` should work fine for the English text.\n\nWait, let me re-read the user's actual command. They wrote:\n```\nfindstr /C\" 1.\" build\\err.txt > nul\n```\n\nvs the C++ test which had:\n```\nfindstr /C:\" 1.\" build\\err.txt > nul\n```\n\nYes, the missing colon after `/C` is the problem! In `findstr`, you need `/C:\"search text\"` (with colon and quotes), not `/C\"search text\"`.\n\nThe C++ version correctly uses `/C:\" 1.\"` with the colon.\n\nLet me also check if the user's `echo 2 3 bam` will work. In cmd (batch), `echo 2 3 bam` outputs \"2 3 bam\\n\" which goes to stdin of `main.exe`. Then `get_string` reads it, `strtod` parses \"2\" and \"3\", then encounters \"bam\" — which triggers `end_ptr == start_ptr` check → exit 65.\n\nActually wait, 2 3 bam - three tokens. strtod would parse \"2\" (end_ptr at space, OK), then \"3\" (end_ptr at space, OK), then \"bam\" - strtod returns 0, end_ptr = start_ptr. `end_ptr == start_ptr` check would trigger → exit 65 with diagnostic.\n\nActually wait. Let me re-trace: \"2 3 bam\"\n- strtod(\"2 3 bam\") → 2.0, end_ptr = \" 3 bam\". `*end_ptr = ' '` → OK.\n- strtod(\" 3 bam\") → 3.0, end_ptr = \" bam\". `*end_ptr = ' '` → OK.\n- strtod(\" bam\") → strtod skips the space, tries to parse \"bam\" → 0.0, end_ptr = \" bam\" (nptr stored). So end_ptr = start_ptr → `end_ptr == start_ptr` → TRUE → error exit 65.\n\nWait, but `start_ptr` after the second iteration was advanced past \"3 \" to \" bam\". The third strtod receives \" bam\". If no conversion occurs, end_ptr = nptr = start_ptr (the original pointer passed in, which is \" bam\"). So `*end_ptr = ' '`. In that case, `end_ptr == start_ptr` → TRUE, but `*end_ptr != ' ' && *end_ptr != '\\0'` → FALSE because `*end_ptr` IS a space.\n\nSo my check `end_ptr == start_ptr` catches it! Good. Exit code 65.\n\nBut wait, the user said \"echo 2 3 bam\" — this is fine. The issue they're reporting is about `findstr` syntax, not about the program behavior.\n\nLet me explain the `findstr` syntax issue clearly.",
